{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473998"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:16:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11687"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11687"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.58,0.12,0.05,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4302"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56055"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4302"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11687"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41606"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1422"},{"type":"tags","id":"2187"},{"type":"tags","id":"2287"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6759"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44105"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56055"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-month-old boy is brought in by his mother to the General Practice clinic for his routine vaccinations. He is due for his meningococcal ACWY, measles, mumps and rubella, and pneumococcal vaccines. Additionally, he is eligible for an influenza vaccination. The mother asks about the child receiving the vaccines as the boy is currently unwell. He has had a four-day history of rhinorrhoea which is improving, and no other symptoms. The child is normally fit and well. He is feeding well, active, and has normal wet nappies. He has been sleeping as normal. On examination, he appears alert and active. He is afebrile and central capillary refill is two seconds. His chest is clear on auscultation with no work of breathing observed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Give all vaccines when the child is fully recovered","It is safe to give all vaccines now","Give the meningococcal ACWY and pneumococcal vaccines only","Give all vaccines except the influenza vaccine","Give all vaccines four weeks after the child has fully recovered"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen considering vaccination in children with concurrent illnesses, it\u0027s important to distinguish between mild and more severe conditions. \u003Cstrong\u003EIt is safe to give all vaccines now\u003C/strong\u003E because the child\u0027s illness is mild and improving. The boy has only rhinorrhoea (runny nose) which has been getting better over four days. He is otherwise well, feeding normally, active, and afebrile. These are all indicators of a mild, self-limiting upper respiratory tract infection, likely a common cold.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent immunisation guidelines, including those from the World Health Organization and the Australian Immunisation Guidelines consistently state that mild illnesses are not contraindications to vaccination. This includes minor upper respiratory tract infections and low-grade fevers. The rationale behind this is that the immune response to vaccines is not significantly affected by mild illnesses, and the risk of adverse reactions is not increased.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiving all vaccines when the child is fully recovered\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Egiving all vaccines four weeks after the child has fully recovered\u003C/strong\u003E are unnecessary delays. Such delays can leave the child vulnerable to vaccine-preventable diseases for longer than necessary. Moreover, they may lead to missed opportunities for vaccination if the family doesn\u0027t return for a follow-up appointment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiving the meningococcal ACWY and pneumococcal vaccines only\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it would result in incomplete immunisation. There\u0027s no medical reason to withhold any of the scheduled vaccines in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGiving all vaccines except the influenza vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is also not appropriate. The influenza vaccine is just as safe to administer during mild illnesses as the other vaccines. There is no scientific basis for withholding the influenza vaccine while administering the others. All recommended vaccines, including the influenza vaccine, should be given to provide comprehensive protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s crucial to note that there are situations where vaccination should be delayed. These include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EModerate to severe illness, especially with high fever (\u226538.5\u00b0C)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EConditions requiring hospitalisation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESpecific contraindications for individual vaccines (e.g., severe allergies to vaccine components)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ECertain immunocompromised states for live vaccines\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn these cases, vaccination should be postponed until the condition improves or specialist advice is sought. However, the mild rhinorrhoea described in this scenario does not meet these criteria for postponement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy proceeding with all scheduled vaccinations, we ensure timely protection against serious diseases while adhering to evidence-based guidelines. It\u0027s also an opportunity to educate parents about the safety and importance of vaccination, even during mild illnesses, which can help improve vaccination rates and public health outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mild illnesses, such as the common cold, are not contraindications to vaccination, and delaying vaccines unnecessarily can leave children vulnerable to preventable diseases."],"references":["Lapphra K, Scheifele D. Can children with minor illnesses be safely immunized? Paediatr Child Health. 2011 Oct;16(8):463. doi: 10.1093/pch/16.8.463. PMID: 23024581; PMCID: PMC3202382. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3202382/","Getting vaccinated [Internet]. Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. 2023. Available at: https://www.health.gov.au/childhood-immunisation/getting-vaccinated","Vaccination for people who are immunocompromised. In:  Australian Immunisation Handbook [online]. 2023. Available at: https://immunisationhandbook.health.gov.au/contents/vaccination-for-special-risk-groups/vaccination-for-people-who-are-immunocompromised#use-of-live-vaccines-in-people-who-are-immunocompromised"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41606"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11687"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41606","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41606"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T10:16:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T10:18:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4302"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56055"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":